{
  "doc_id": "14737",
  "text": "Fibrosis is a chronic pathological consequence of inflammatory responses [CITATION_1] . Often occurring as the end result of Th2-type responses, it leads to distortion of tissues and organs, sometimes impairing their functions [CITATION_2] . Fibrosis is characterized by de novo production and deposition of ECM proteins, such as collagens, fibronectin, elastin, proteoglycans, and laminin. Although maintenance of tissue structure is the main function of ECM proteins, some of them, such as osteopontin and tenascin-C, modulate immune responses by interacting with immune or nonimmune cells; these are termed matricellular proteins [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
